</div>

<button class="accordion">Can a UTI cause sepsis?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Untreated urinary tract infections may spread to the kidney, causing more pain and illness, and it can also cause sepsis. The term urosepsis is usually used to describe sepsis caused by a UTI. Sometimes incorrectly called blood poisoning, sepsis is the body's often deadly response to infection or injury.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">How is sepsis tested?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>If your doctor believes you might have sepsis, he'll do an exam and run tests to look for the following: Bacteria in the blood or other body fluids.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion">What causes confusion in sepsis?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The encephalopathy in sepsis is considered a diffuse cerebral dysfunction as a consequence of the systemic inflammatory response to an infection, with no direct central nervous system infection. The stress response is physiologically triggered by an activating signal that is mediated by two pathways.</p>
